Column parsers

Each parser comes in two forms: parse_xxx() which is used to parse vectors that already exist in R and col_xxx() which is used to parse vectors as they are loaded by a read_xxx() function.

parse_logical
parse_integer
parse_double
parse_character
col_logical
col_integer
col_double
col_character
col_euro_double
parse_euro_double
col_numeric
parse_numeric
Parse logicals, integers, and reals
parse_datetime
parse_date
parse_time
col_datetime
col_date
col_time
Parse date/times
parse_factor
col_factor
Parse factors
parse_guess
col_guess
guess_parser
Parse using the "best" type
parse_number
col_number
Parse numbers, flexibly

Locale

The “locale” controls all options that vary from country-to-country or language-to-language.

date_names
date_names_lang
date_names_langs
Create or retrieve date names
locale
default_locale
Create locales

Write

Despite its name, readr also provides a number of functions to write to disk.

format_delim
format_csv
format_tsv
Convert a data frame to a delimited string
write_delim
write_csv
write_excel_csv
write_tsv
Save a data frame to a delimited file.

Debugging weird files

These functions are helpful for debugging files that don’t parse correctly.

count_fields
Count the number of fields in each line of a file.
guess_encoding
Guess encoding of file.
type_convert
Re-convert character columns in existing data frame.
